  "text": "This sub-section describes the process of extracting the minutiae points from the fingerprint image. We chose fingerprint biometrics chiefly because of its two significant characteristics: uniqueness and permanence (ability to remain unchanged over the lifetime). A fingerprint can be described as a pattern of ridges and valleys found on the surface of a fingertip. The ridges of the finger form the so-called minutiae points: ridge endings (terminals of ridge lines) and ridge bifurcations (fork-like structures) [CITATION_1] . These minutiae points serve as an important means of fingerprint recognition. The steps involved in the proposed approach for minutiae extraction are as follows,",
